  },
  "confusionGroups": [
    {
      "id": "particle_subject_topic",
      "label": "Subject vs Topic (は vs が)",
      "description": "は marks the topic (what you are talking about); が marks the subject (who/what does the action)",
      "members": ["n5-particle-wa", "n5-particle-ga-subject"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "は for known information, general statements, and setting the topic. が for new/specific information, emphasizing the subject, and with existential verbs. 「私は学生です」(topic) vs 「私が行きます」(it is I who will go, emphasis). は can replace が/を when they are the topic; が cannot replace は for pure topic-setting."
    },
    {
      "id": "particle_location",
      "label": "Location: Existence vs Action (に vs で)",
      "description": "に marks location of existence (where something is); で marks location of action (where something happens)",
      "members": ["n5-particle-ni-location", "n5-particle-de"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "に for static location with ある/いる: 「公園に犬がいる」(dog exists at park). で for active location: 「公園で遊ぶ」(play at park). Key test: can you substitute ある/いる? Yes → に. Is it an action happening somewhere? → で."
    },
    {
      "id": "particle_direction",
      "label": "Direction Particles (に vs へ)",
      "description": "Both に and へ express direction/destination; へ emphasizes the direction itself",
      "members": ["n5-particle-ni-location", "n5-particle-he", "n5-particle-ni-he"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "Both are largely interchangeable for direction with movement verbs (行く/来る/帰る). に is more versatile (also time, location, indirect object). へ stresses the direction/destination more. For arrival/attachment に is required: 「椅子に座る」. へ cannot replace に for time or indirect objects."
    },
    {
      "id": "particle_object_means",
      "label": "Object vs Means (を vs で)",
      "description": "を marks the direct object of a transitive verb; で marks the means or tool used",
      "members": ["n5-particle-wo", "n5-particle-de"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "を marks what is acted upon: 「ご飯を食べる」(eat rice). で marks what is used to do it: 「箸で食べる」(eat with chopsticks). Both can appear in one sentence: 「ペンで手紙を書く」(write a letter with a pen)."
    },
    {
      "id": "existence_verbs",
      "label": "Existence Verbs (ある vs いる)",
      "description": "ある for non-living things; いる for living things (people and animals)",
      "members": ["n5-exist-ga-aru", "n5-exist-ga-iru"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "ある = inanimate objects, concepts, events, scheduled things: 「本がある」「授業がある」. いる = animate beings (people, animals): 「犬がいる」「先生がいる」. Edge case: robots and plants — いる can be used for loved/personified things. Phones/cars → ある even though modern usage varies."
    },
    {
      "id": "copula_forms",
      "label": "Copula Forms (だ / です / じゃない / ではない)",
      "description": "Plain and polite affirmative/negative forms of the copula",
      "members": ["n5-copula-da", "n5-copula-janai"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "だ = plain/casual affirmative. です = polite affirmative. じゃない = casual negative (contraction of では+ない). ではない = formal negative. Past: だった / でした / じゃなかった / ではなかった. じゃ is casual spoken; では is written/formal. Both mean the same thing."
    },
    {
      "id": "conjecture_forms",
      "label": "Conjecture Forms (だろう vs でしょう)",
      "description": "Plain and polite forms of conjecture/probability",
      "members": ["n5-copula-darou", "n5-copula-deshou"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "だろう = plain conjecture (probably, I think). でしょう = polite conjecture, also used as tag question seeking agreement (「そうでしょう?」). Both follow plain/polite register of the sentence. でしょう at end of statement = 'right?'; at end of question = just polite."
    },
    {
      "id": "te_form_requests",
      "label": "Te-form Requests & Permission",
      "description": "Forms built on the て-form expressing requests, permission, and prohibition",
      "members": ["n5-verb-te-kudasai", "n5-verb-te-mo-ii", "n5-verb-te-wa-ikenai", "n5-verb-nai-de-kudasai", "n5-verb-cha-ikenai"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "てください = polite request (please do). てもいい = permission (it's OK to). てはいけない = prohibition (must not). ないでください = polite request not to do. ちゃいけない = casual spoken prohibition (てはいけない contraction). Register progression: てください (polite) > ちゃいけない (casual)."
    },
    {
      "id": "obligation_forms",
      "label": "Must / Obligation Forms",
      "description": "Multiple expressions meaning 'must do' ranging from casual to formal",
      "members": ["n5-must-nakereba-naranai", "n5-must-nakute-naranai", "n5-must-naito-ikenai", "n5-must-nakucha"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "All express obligation. なくてはいけない = standard spoken must (negative condition + cannot be bad). なくてはならない = formal/written variant. ないといけない = conditional must (common in casual speech). なくちゃ = very casual contraction of なくては. All translate to 'must do / have to do'. None interchangeable with なくてもいい (don't have to)."
    },
    {
      "id": "desire_intent",
      "label": "Desire & Intent (たい / ほしい / つもり / ほうがいい)",
      "description": "Expressions for personal desire, wanting objects, plans, and advice",
      "members": ["n5-verb-tai", "n5-want-ga-hoshii", "n5-intent-tsumori", "n5-should-hou-ga-ii"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "たい = want to DO (verb desire, 1st person): 「行きたい」. がほしい = want to HAVE (noun desire): 「新しい車がほしい」. つもり = intend to / plan to: 「来週行くつもりだ」. ほうがいい = had better / should (advice): 「早く寝たほうがいい」. たい conjugates like い-adj; ほしい also conjugates like い-adj."
    },
    {
      "id": "reason_cause",
      "label": "Reason / Cause (から vs ので)",
      "description": "Two ways to say 'because': から (subjective/assertive) vs ので (objective/soft)",
      "members": ["n5-reason-kara", "n5-reason-node"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "から = spoken, subjective reason, can sound assertive or blunt: 「眠いから帰る」. ので = more objective, polite, shows the reason gently: 「眠いので帰ります」. ので pairs better with polite endings; から is neutral to register. Rule of thumb: use ので in formal/written; から in casual speech."
    },
    {
      "id": "contrast_conjunction",
      "label": "Contrast Conjunctions (が / けど / けれども / しかし / でも)",
      "description": "Multiple ways to say 'but/however' with varying formality",
      "members": ["n5-particle-ga-contrast", "n5-conj-kedo", "n5-conj-keredomo", "n5-conj-shikashi", "n5-particle-de-mo"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "が (clause-internal) = softest 'but', often polite. けど = casual spoken contrast. けれども = more formal than けど. しかし = formal written, starts a new sentence. でも = casual sentence-starter. Formality: しかし > けれども > が > けど ≈ でも. でも and しかし only start sentences; が/けど/けれども connect two clauses in one sentence."
    },
    {
      "id": "question_words",
      "label": "Question Words (疑問詞)",
      "description": "Interrogative words: what, how much, why, how, what kind",
      "members": ["n5-qw-nani", "n5-qw-ikura", "n5-qw-doshite", "n5-qw-douyatte", "n5-qw-donna"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "何/なに = what (general). なん = what (before counters and です: 何歳, 何ですか). いくら = how much (price). どうして = why (also casual). どうやって = how (by what means/method). どんな = what kind of (attributive, before nouns). All are interrogative pronouns that stay in situ in Japanese (not fronted like in English)."
    },
    {
      "id": "demonstratives",
      "label": "Ko-So-A-Do Demonstratives",
      "description": "The three-way distance system: near speaker (ko-), near listener (so-), far from both (a-)",
      "members": ["n5-dem-kore-sore-are", "n5-dem-kono-sono-ano", "n5-dem-koko-soko-asoko"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "Ko- = near speaker (これ/この/ここ). So- = near listener or previously mentioned (それ/その/そこ). A- = far from both or shared knowledge (あれ/あの/あそこ). これ/それ/あれ = standalone pronouns (this/that thing). この/その/あの = prenominal modifiers (this/that + noun). ここ/そこ/あそこ = locations (here/there/over there)."
    },
    {
      "id": "time_sequence",
      "label": "Time & Sequence (前に / てから / まだ / もう)",
      "description": "Temporal expressions: before, after doing, still/not yet, already/anymore",
      "members": ["n5-time-mae-ni", "n5-verb-te-kara", "n5-adv-mada", "n5-adv-mou", "n5-time-mada-te-imasen"],
      "pedagogicalNote": "前に = before (dictionary form + 前に). てから = after doing (て-form + から, then next action). まだ = still (+ positive); not yet (+ negative). もう = already (+ positive); not anymore (+ negative). Common error: confusing まだ (still/not yet) with もう (already/anymore). 「まだ食べていません」 = haven't eaten yet vs 「もう食べました」 = already ate."
    }
  ],
  "synonymGroups": [
    {
      "id": "syn_direction",
      "members": ["n5-particle-ni-location", "n5-particle-he"],
      "reason": "に and へ are largely interchangeable for expressing direction/destination with movement verbs (行く, 来る, 帰る). へ emphasizes directionality; に is more general."
    },
    {
      "id": "syn_why",
      "members": ["n5-qw-doshite"],
      "note": "どうして and なぜ (not in N5 arch but related) both mean 'why'. どうして is more conversational; なぜ more formal/written.",
      "reason": "どうして = why (casual/spoken). At N5 level only どうして is listed, but learners encounter なぜ in reading."
    },
    {
      "id": "syn_but",
      "members": ["n5-conj-kedo", "n5-conj-keredomo"],
      "reason": "けど and けれども are the same word at different formality levels. けど = casual/spoken; けれども = slightly more formal. Both contrast two clauses within a sentence."
    },
    {
      "id": "syn_must",
      "members": ["n5-must-nakereba-naranai", "n5-must-nakute-naranai", "n5-must-naito-ikenai", "n5-must-nakucha", "n5-verb-cha-ikenai"],
      "reason": "All express obligation ('must do'/'have to do') with different levels of formality and construction. なくちゃ (casual) through なくてはならない (formal). ちゃいけない expresses prohibition ('must not') — related but opposite in polarity."
    }
  ],
